ody's talking to me, so I'm not quite\nsure what's going on. ","index":"00403","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> One moment, please. ","index":"00404","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLamont:</b> Translation from the floor, Madam Speaker?","index":"00405","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> This has something to do with the member needing to, firstly, mute\noriginal audio if the member is going to speak in French, and then unmute when\nhe finishes. Is the member good to go with that? ","index":"00406","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLamont:</b> Okay, that I think I can do. ","index":"00407","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> Go ahead, then. <i>[interjection]</i> No, the member's muted his\nown audio. ","index":"00408","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I'm\ngoing to suggest that we are going to have&nbsp;&nbsp;somebody phone the member\nand help him&nbsp;&nbsp;work through the technology of that, and then, in&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the\nmeantime, we are going to call the honourable&nbsp;&nbsp;Minister of\nConservation and Climate, and then we will come back to the honourable member\nfor St. Boniface after somebody will give him a call.","index":"00409","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>����� </b>So\nwe will call now for debate, the honourable Minister of Conservation and\nClimate. ","index":"00410","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nSarah </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69198497\">Guillemard</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Conservation and Climate):</b> As the Minister of Conservation and Climate,\nI am happy to speak to the many aspects of Budget&nbsp;2021 that will improve\nour environmental resilience, reduce GHG emissions and move Manitoban closer to\nbeing the cleanest, greenest, most climate-resilient province in Canada.","index":"00411","speaker":"Sarah Guillemard"},{"html":"����� I'll\nstart with our recently announced Green Impact Bonds, a first of its kind in\nManitoba organics green bond. A joint initiative with the Department of\nFamilies, this program is facilitated through the�through Innovative NRG, a\nManitoba-based waste and energy company. They will use their patented\ninnovative technology to process organic waste such as animal byproducts and\nwastewater sludge through a gasification process. ","index":"00412","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thermal\nenergy released in this process will be captured and used to heat buildings or\nwater for industrial processes, thereby reducing use of fossil fuels. ","index":"00413","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\ntechnology is a made-in-Manitoba innovative clean tech solution. This is a new\napproach to supporting green projects. It signals progress on the\nMade-in-Manitoba Climate and Green Plan, the carbon savings account and growth\nin Manitoba's green economy. ","index":"00414","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Madam\nSpeaker, $1.2 million has been commit�ted for our Climate and Green Plan\nImplementation Office, allowing the resources required to ensure that our\nMade-in-Manitoba Climate and Green Plan advances the important government-wide\nprojects and initiatives this government is implementing to continue to protect\nour environment.","index":"00415","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I look\nforward to another great year of work from the office and I'm excited to move forward\nwith 2021's programming. ","index":"00416","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Our\nConservation and Climate Fund, up this year&nbsp;to a total of a million\ndollars, is a results-based pro�gram designed to provide funding to exciting\nand innovative carbon reduction projects that align with our Made-in-Manitoba\nClimate and Green Plan. ","index":"00417","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Through\na competitive process municipalities, non-profits, Indigenous communities and\nbusinesses can pitch projects to the fund to reduce GHG emissions in Manitoba.\nLast year's intake saw eight&nbsp;&nbsp;successful proponents and I look\nforward to launching this year's intake and funding some exciting GHG-reducing\nprojects.","index":"00418","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\nknow that Manitobans expect smart invest�ments that will help us become\nCanada's most climate-resilient province. Our budget speech had a sneak peak at\nsomething that I'm excited to provide more details on in the near future�a\n$20-million endowment fund for the jewels of this province�our parks. As a\nreminder to the House, our parks are not for sale. ","index":"00419","speaker":""},{"html":"����� While\nthe members opposite continue to fear monger Manitobans, this government is\ncommitted to&nbsp;improving Manitobans' adventures in nature. Our\nMade-in-Manitoba Climate and Green Plan protects Manitobans from a high and\never-rising federal carbon tax. Manitoba deserves to be recognized for its\nclean, green grid and the billions of dollars that have been invested in clean\nenergy in this province. ","index":"00420","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\nwill continue to advocate for fair treatment of Manitobans. ","index":"00421","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Our\nplan is better for Manitoba's environment and Manitoba's economy. ","index":"00422","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Conservation\nand climate isn't the only depart�ment in this government making green\ncommitments. Infrastructure, Municipal Relations, Agriculture and Resource\nDevelopment, and Central Services have budget items that continue to show that\nthis government is committed to keeping our environment clean, our communities\nand waterways safe, and our GHG emissions trending down. ","index":"00423","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Some\nof these initiatives include $101 million for the Lake Manitoba Lake St. Martin\noutlet project to prevent floods, $100 million for potential emergencies such\nas floods, forest fires, and drought, $126 million for the North End Water\nPollution Control Centre, and we're also committing to new electric bus infra�structure\nin Winnipeg. ","index":"00424","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We are\nalso increasing the Watershed Districts Program funding to near $6 million,\nmitigating floods and drought, supporting farmers and municipalities and, most\nimportantly, protecting our water quality. ","index":"00425","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Budget\n2021 once again proves this government's commitment to climate mitigation in\nManitoba unquestionably. We're implementing initiatives that will help us meet\nour 2022 carbon savings account goals and moving forward with exciting projects\nthat will help mitigate and reduce Manitoba's carbon impact. ","index":"00426","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I'm\nquite happy with my department and this government's progress on our climate\nfile, and am&nbsp;&nbsp;excited to bring forward 2021's initiatives for\nManitobans. ","index":"00427","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\nwill become Canada's cleanest, greenest, most climate-resilient province by\nworking to�gether&nbsp;with Manitobans, innovators, municipalities, Indigenous\ngroups, and business to implement what works for Manitoba.","index":"00428","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As the\nMLA for Fort Richmond, many of the other aspects of the budget speak volumes to\nmy constituents. Budget 2021's additional $4 million in bursaries for\npost-secondary students, additional $1.4&nbsp;&nbsp;million in interest-free\nstudent loans and $700&nbsp;million to post-secondary students mean more\nsuccess for our students. ","index":"00429","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(15:00)","index":"00430","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nis an important priority for me, as the representative for Fort Richmond, and\nthe thousands of students who live within my constituency. ","index":"00431","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Due to\nthis pandemic, I think that we all could use a break. Thankfully, this\ngovernment is implementing tax breaks that will put money back on Manitobans'\ntables and help them to worry less about their bottom line. Thanks to\ninitiatives like our $2,020-tax-rollback guarantee, this government is keeping\ntheir promise.","index":"00432","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Phasing\nout the education property tax means equal footing for Manitoba students and\nfinancial relief for property owners. We're reducing property taxes by 50 per\ncent over the next two years for residential and farm properties. That's an\naverage rebate of over�of $800 over the 2-year period.","index":"00433","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I know\nmany of my constituents and many Manitobans could use the extra money after the\nyear that we've gone through. ","index":"00434","speaker":""},{"html":"����� On a\npersonal note, I was ecstatic to see this government continues to protect\nManitobans by providing continuous glucose-monitoring devices to children and\nyouth under 25, and expanding the insulin pump program. ","index":"00435","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\nwould like to make a special shout-out thank‑you to Mrs. Dorothy Ross and\nPatrick Tohill of the JDRF national team, who have advocated very respectfully\nand well over the last 5 years that I have been a part of this government, and\nI know that they celebrate these achievements along with our government.","index":"00436","speaker":""},{"html":"<i>Mr. Len\nIsleifson, Acting Speaker, in the Chair</i> ","index":"00437","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr.\nDeputy Speaker, I remember advocating during the previous NDP government to\nimplement a program that would cover the cost of insulin pumps for children\nunder 18, and it was an arduous, long process, and I celebrated when there was\nan announcement made to cover up to 17 years old.","index":"00438","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As a\nmother of a type 1 diabetic child, ultimately, the goal is for a cure, and the\ninvestments in the research, I believe, will one day achieve that ultimate\ngoal. All advocacy groups aim for a cure, but in the meantime, the supports\nthat are offered through various governments are much appreciated, and I know\nthat they would go a long way for the health of Manitobans living with type 1\ndiabetes.","index":"00439","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr.\nDeputy Speaker, rent control guidelines freezes means that there are more\nsecurity for renters, of whom many have struggled in the past year due to the\nCOVID-19 panic�pandemic. Child care�or, child-care free freezes and $22 million\nfor rent assist also means more support for Manitobans who need it most.","index":"00440","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Budget\n2021 has prioritized many things. Manitoba families, students, health care,\neducation, environmental mitigation and the COVID-19 response. This means more\nsupport for Manitobans now, when all are struggling. ","index":"00441","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou, Mr. Deputy Speaker, for allowing me to speak to this year's budget. ","index":"00442","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>The\nActing Speaker (Len Isleifson): </b>We will now revert back to the member from\nSt. Boniface, who has nine minutes remaining. ","index":"00443","speaker":"Len Isleifson"},{"html":"<b><span lang=\"FR-CA\">Mr. Lamont:</span></b><span lang=\"FR-CA\"> </span><span lang=\"FR-CA\">Merci. Et ce qui�et ce que fait ce budget c'est pas tant un budget\nqu'un vol; c'est un pillage massif du tr�sor public, o� nous allons emprunter\ndes milliards de dollars pour faire des ch�ques aux vaillants pipelines du\nManitoba.</span>","index":"00444","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">Il n'y a pas que les propri�taires, et le Premier\nministre (M.&nbsp;Pallister) aime bien parler de la table de cuisine, mais tout\ncela va aller � la table du conseil d'administration. C'est compl�tement\ninacceptable en temps de crise. </span>","index":"00445","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">Ce qu'il faut maintenant c'est de l'�quit�; ce dont\nnous avons besoin en ce moment c'est de l'honn�tet�, surtout en ce qui concerne\nles v�rit�s dures. Mais quand on nous dit cela&nbsp;: Vous savez qu'il y aura\n400&nbsp;&nbsp;� 800 pi�ces aux cours des deux prochaines ann�es pour le\nManitobain moyen c'est-�-dire, encore une fois, avec le budget, nous continuons\nde regrouper plusieurs ann�es.</span>","index":"00446","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">On ne cesse d'exag�rer les chiffres; on entend dire\nque, parce que trois ans, les investissements dans l'infrastructure ont �t�\nregroup�s pour donner l'impression d'�tre plus gros. Et le gouvernement a\ntoujours promis des choses qu'il n'a jamais faites.</span>","index":"00447","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">����� Ils ont toujours exag�r�; ils ont toujours �t�\nsous-performant; </span><span lang=\"FR-CA\">ils promettent de l'or et livrent de\nla pyrite parce que � 400&nbsp;$ par m�nage, c'est 200&nbsp;$�c'est-�-dire deux\nmois�et plus que 50 pourcent des Manitobains sont actuellement � 200&nbsp;$ de\nl'insolvabilit�.</span>","index":"00448","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">Les ch�ques pour les imp�ts de la\npropri�t� seront&nbsp;&nbsp;donc couverts pendant deux mois, et cela va co�ter\ndes milliards � tout le monde parce que nous allons tous devoir les rembourser.\nC'est de l'argent � emprunter. Nous allons ajouter 8 milliards de dollars au\nd�ficit pour payer cela, et cela va aller aux propri�t�s commerciales et aux\npropri�taires des propri�t�s commerciales.</span>","index":"00449","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">Plusieurs personnes ayant plusieurs\nfermes pourront recevoir plusieurs ch�ques. Les gens qui ont plusieurs\npropri�t�s pourront obtenir plusieurs ch�ques. La concentration de la propri�t�\nest bien pire que la concentration des revenus.</span>","index":"00450","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"FR-CA\">C'est donc l'une des r�ductions\nd'imp�ts les plus injustes que vous puissiez imaginer; les gens qui sont au\nsommet de l'�chelle des revenus, qui poss�dent des dizaines de milliers d'acres\nde terre agricoles, des gens qui poss�dent des centaines de millions de dollars\nde biens immobiliers obtiendront des